## How the security requirements are met

| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| SQL injection | `better-sqlite3` prepared statements with `?` placeholders everywhere |
| Password hashing | bcrypt, cost 12, salted |
| Input validation/sanitisation | `express-validator` length/charset/type rules + 64 kb body cap |
| XSS | EJS `<%= %>` context-aware escaping + strict CSP (no inline scripts) |
| CSRF | Per-session synchronizer token on every state-changing request, constant-time compare, `SameSite=Lax` |
| Access control / IDOR | All admin queries scoped to `author_id`; foreign IDs return 404 |
| Secure cookies | `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` (via `COOKIE_SECURE`); session regenerated on login (anti-fixation) |
| Security headers | Helmet (CSP, frame-ancestors, nosniff, referrer-policy) |
| No error leakage | Central handler logs server-side, returns generic messages |
| No hardcoded secrets | All from env vars; prod refuses to start without `SESSION_SECRET` |

Plus login **rate-limiting** with generic failure messages (user-enumeration defence).

