## How the security requirements are met

- **SQL injection** — every query uses `?` placeholders; no string-built SQL anywhere.
- **Password hashing** — `bcrypt` with per-password salt; a dummy hash equalises login timing to blunt username enumeration.
- **XSS** — Jinja2 auto-escaping (no `|safe`); newlines preserved via CSS `white-space:pre-wrap`, not raw HTML. Strict CSP (`default-src 'self'`, no inline scripts/styles).
- **CSRF** — Flask-WTF `CSRFProtect`; every state-changing POST (publish/edit/delete/comment/login/logout) carries a `csrf_token`.
- **Access control / IDOR** — edit and delete re-fetch the article and `abort(403)` unless `author_id == current_user.id`.
- **Session cookies** — `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, and `Secure` (env-toggled via `COOKIE_SECURE`); session cleared and rotated on login.
- **Security headers** — CSP, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, `Referrer-Policy`, `Permissions-Policy`.
- **No error leakage** — custom 400/403/404/500/CSRF pages; `debug=False`.
- **Secrets** — `SECRET_KEY` read from env; the app refuses to start if it's unset (fails closed).
- **Bonus** — input validation/length caps, 1 MB request cap, and a relative-only `next` redirect to prevent open redirects.

One note on local dev: keep `COOKIE_SECURE=false` (the `.env.example` default) when serving plain HTTP on localhost, otherwise the browser won't return the session cookie and login won't persist. Set it to `true` in production behind HTTPS.

