## How each mandatory control is met

- **SQLi** — every query uses `?` parameter binding; no string interpolation.
- **Passwords** — Argon2id (`argon2-cffi`), per-password salt, auto-rehash, constant-ish-time login (hashes even when the user doesn't exist).
- **XSS** — Jinja2 context-aware autoescaping everywhere + strict CSP (`default-src 'self'`, no inline script).
- **CSRF** — Flask-WTF `CSRFProtect`; token on every POST (contact, login, logout, delete).
- **Access control / IDOR** — admin routes require an authenticated session; delete acts only via the server-side session identity and 404s on missing rows.
- **Session cookies** — `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` (when HTTPS); session cleared on login to prevent fixation.
- **Headers** — CSP, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `X-Frame-Options: DENY`, `Referrer-Policy`, `Permissions-Policy`, HSTS on HTTPS.
- **No leaks** — `debug=False`, generic error pages, full detail logged server-side only; `HTTPException` handler preserves real status codes without exposing internals.
- **Secrets** — all from env vars.
- **Open redirect** — post-login `next` restricted to local paths.

## SSRF guard (`fetch_preview`)

- http/https **scheme allow-list**.
- Resolves the host and **blocks private/loopback/link-local/reserved/multicast/unspecified** ranges — covers `127.0.0.0/8`, `10/8`, `172.16/12`, `192.168/16`, `169.254/16` (incl. `169.254.169.254`), `::1`, `fc00::/7`.
- **DNS-rebinding defence**: a custom transport adapter re-validates the *actually connected peer IP* at socket-connect time for both HTTP and HTTPS (TLS/SNI left intact since the real hostname is used).
- **Redirects not auto-followed**; each `Location` hop is re-validated (max 3).
- **Connect/read timeouts**, **512 KiB response cap**, and HTML/text content-type check.

